{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_aurora_ver02/data/sn86076142/00415626940/1908011901/0075.xml":{"full_text":"I n -nr., -.r..\ni\nTOXOPAH DAILY BONANZA, TOXOPAH, NEVADA, JANUARY 10, 1008.\n!l\nt\nV'\nl\nin\nii.i\ns\nin\n\nTONOPAH DAILY BONANZA\nPublished Every Morning, Monaay Excepted, at Tonopah, Nevada\nW. W. BOOTH,\nEditor and Proprietor\nUNIONjbLABEL\nJ. S. DAVELER,\nManager\nMember of Associated Press\nTERMS OP SUBSCRIPTION\n;ne year.. fll.OSI Three months\nNine months 10.0 One month\ntlx months ,76 One week\nSubscriptions by mail mu st be paid for in advance.\n3.50\nTEN DOLLARS REWARD\nA reward of $10 Will be paid for In\nformation that will lead to the arrest\nand conviction of parties stealing The\nBonanza from premises of subscribers.\nTO SUBSCRIBERS\nParties who do not receive their\npapers, or who have any cause of com\nprint, will oblige by notifying this\noffice.\nEntered at the Postofflce in Tonopah a:, second class matter.\nEDITORIAL COMMENT\nCONDITIONS ARE IMPROVING.\nBradstreet's and Dun's reports for the week declare that there Is\na better feeling in the financial world. These two commercial agencies\nKeep their fingers on the financial pulse, with their branches in every\ncity, town and hamlet in the United States, and correspondents in all\nthe European cities, and it is well to give heed when they speak.\nWe can readily understand that conditions are improving, and why\nthey are improving. Whether the panic through which we have passed\nwas an artificial one, caused by the reprisals of the men of wealth\nagainst the administration, or whether it was the natural outcome of con\nditions, makes little difference; the result was the same. But when\nwe stop to consider that the products of the soil were, in money,\n000,000,000. it is little wonder that conditions would improve once\nthat great mass of wealth was set in motion.\nWe have seen the improvement in the situation day by day and\nweek by week. The story was told in the dispatches in the employ\nment by the big industrial institutions of the men who had been dis\ncharged for lack of work some months ago. Day after day we read of\nTiundreds and thousands of men returning to work, and this means the\nreturn of prosperity throughout the land. The money that is paid out\nfor labor is the money which finds general circulation, and it flows\ninto all channel. It goes to the butcher, the baker, the merchant, the\nbank; it goes from the bank to the investor, and promotes all kinds of in\ndustry. When money is free times are good, when money is tight, times\nare bad.\nTimes are hard at present, for the reason that while money is grad\nually loosening up, it is being used as sparingly and as cautiously as\npossible; and this will be the case until the complete return of confi\ndence. That time is bound to come, is on the way now. We are strug\ngling with the fetters of the panic, and we are having a time shaking\nthem off. We must be patient awhile longer- we must grit our teeth,\nand put our shoulder to the wheel, and we will pull through. Pluck al\nways wins.\nBoni and Sagan have had another fight, with the usual accompani\nment of face spitting. Americans are often criticised by punctilious\nFrench for their too liberal use of cuspidors. Now it is possible for\nus to retort that the despised spittoon has some advantages over the\nhuman face, which seems to invite expectoration in Paris when fortune\nhunters run afoul of each other. S. F. Chronicle.\nForty indictments against Schmitz and one hundred and seventeen\nagainst Ruef is pretty good evidence that there are a number of legal\nhurdles to jump yet before they can consider that the judicial chase is\nover and they are free from the clutches of the law. Miner-Transcript.\nATTACKS INDICTMENT.\nSAN FRANCISCO, Jan. 18. Jas.\nTreadwell, indicted on a charge of\nembezzling the funds of the Califor\nnia Safe Deposit and Trust Company,\nw'as in Judge Dunne's court yester\nday to plead, but his attorney, Lewis\nF. Byiugton, interposed a motion to\nset aside the indictment, which went\nover to Wednesday. Byingtou inti\nmated that he would rely upon the\ncontention already raised by Hiram\nW. Johnson that certain of the Grand\nJurors were prejudiced by their de\nposits in the insolvent bank.\nA visit to the Nevada Club means\nthat you will be a steady patron.\nYour friends will be there to greet\nyou. tf\nCaught With the Gold\n.SV til.,..\n.i least mat is wiiat toe assayer said. The last two\nsamples which .Manager Corns sent in from the Pedro\nshowed gold values of $16.1.70 and $47.30. These were\ntaken from a breast of IIGHT FEET of solid ore, the\nfirst of the sulphides and t he second of the oxides. Tie says\nthere is about half and half in the vein and this makes the\ngeneral average of EIGHT FEET of ore to be $106.50 per\nton With eight feet of the vein giving such great gold\nf values and surface workings having proved it for a distance\nof over 300 feet, we have become rather positive that\nabout next Christmas th e Pedro will begin the distribu-\ntion of dividends to its st ockholders. This sounds pretty\ngood and the beauty of it is. we guarantee it to be true. It\nonly requires three days to go there and back. Suppose you\nmake the trip we'll refu n'd the expense, if the mine isn't\njust exactly as we say.\nliAXGLKY.TIUMin.K COMPANY'\nA DIAMOND FOR A DOLLARS\nOn Monday morning at 9 o'clock, we will place on sale a number\nof packages, each containing some a rticle of jewelry, silverware, etc.\nOne of the packages will contain a diamond ring, which package will he\nsold with the rest at 91.00 EACH. Who will be the luckv purchaser'\nGEO. F. BLAKESLEE\nTIm Progressive Jeweler\nN. B. Each article contained in the packages is worth not less than\n$1.00; many are worth more.\nOIL WELLS YIELD\nIMMENSE\nRETURNS\nLOS ANGELES, Jan. 18. The\nUnion Oil Company of California\nmade wonderful strides last year,\nmore than doubling its net earnings\nof the previous year. At the stock\nholders' annual meeting today It was\nshown that the company cleared $2,\n080,771, or 27.G per cent monthly.\nThe dividends average 11.6 per cent\nmonthly. Its land holdings Increase\n62,000 acres, and now are 213.354\nacres, in the choicest of the various\noil districts and are fully developed.\nProsperity was marked alone everv\nline, including production, home and\nforeign contracts and refining. In\nSanta Barbara county the company-\nproduces more than half the oil, and\nin Orange county it Is proving up a\nlarge virgin territory. In the Santa\nMaria field one well is producing\n4300 barrels daily and the outnut\ngenerally is constantly increasing.\nThe company has operated widely\nand its markets for kerosene, ben-,\nzine and lubricants extend from Se\nattle to Mexico. Hawaiian shipments\nhave been increased, a cargo sent to\nChile and Panama, and Union crude\nfuel introduced on the Central Guate-!\nmala railway. I\nNEVADA STATE\nPRISON IS FULL\ncaksun. Jan. IS. William n.\nAtwell. confessed embezzler of the\nfunds of the Searchlight postofflce,\nwill serve his time at McNeil's Island,\nWashington, according to the in\nstructions received yesterday from\nAttorney General Bonaparte. Atwell\nwill serve four years sentence in the\nUnited States prison and pay a fine\nof over $5000; the fine being the\nsame as the amount he embezzled.\nThe attorney general of the United\nStates has also notified the local gov\nernment officials that the United\nStates District Court here may sen\ntence prisoners to serve prison terms\nat McNeil's Island, Washington, in\nstead of the Nevada State penitent!\nary.T The change iu prisons is made\nnecessary on account of the fact that\nthe Nevada prison is now overcrowd\ned and more prisoners cannot well\nbe accommodated.\nVICTIM OF DOPED\nCANDY IS ROBBED\nMAKES LONG TRIP\nTO THRASH RIVAL\nDES MOINES, Jan. 1 8. After\ntraveling all the way from Snohom\nish, Wash., to Des Moines, to recover\nletters which his wife's former sweet\nheart refused to surrender, C. L.\nClemens, a former football star at\nLeland Stanford University, found\nthe man he sought in the office of At\ntorney General Byers at the State\nhouse. There Clemens attacked his\none-time rival, R. H. Dosh, a prom\ninent attorney of Stuart, la.\nThe two men glowered at one an\nother and then began a vicious fight,\nduring which they made their way\nInto the corridors of the capital\nbuilding. Inmates of the scores of\noffices, hearing the confusion, ran ex\ncitedly into the halls and witnessed\nthe terrific beating which the Wash\nington man administered to Dosh. It\ntook the strength of a number of\nmen to pry Clemens from the pros\ntrate attorney, who was picked up\nunconscious and taken to Mercy hos\npital, where it is feared that he will\ndie. He has a fractured skull and\nis otherwise injured.\nClemens was arrested and is held j\nunder heavy bonds on the charge of\nassault to commit murder.\nClemens refused to give the reason i\nfor the assault and Dosh has not re\ncovered sufficiently to talk, but\nfriends of both, who knew that Dosh\nand Mrs. Clemens were sweethearts\nin college at Indianapolis, 12 years\nago, revealed the reason for the assault.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 18. Mrs. Rob-\nert Fox, according to a story told the\npolice, was drugged and robbed while\ni attending a matinee last Saturdav.\ni Last night the police arrested a youn\nwoman who gave her name as Alice\nMoran, who has been charged by\nMrs. Fox with the theft.\nMrs. Fox states that she sat in a\nbox at a theater and got into con\nversation with a young girl who was\nin the same box. The girl admired a\nbracelet which Mrs. Fox wore and\nshe took it off and allowed the girl to\nexamine it. The girl offered Mrs.\nFox some candy, and after eating it\nshe became seriously ill and was as\nsisted from the box by the girl. Mr.\nFox was telephoned for and went to\nthe theater and took his wife home.\nIn the meantime the girl disappeared.\nWhen Mrs. Fox recovered sufficiently\nto leave the theater, she found that\na bag containing $70 and jewelry\nworth $250 were missing, besides the\nbracelet.\nThe physician who attended Mrs.\nFox said she had, without doubt, been\ndrugged, and until yesterday was in\ngrave danger. It is now believed\nthat she will recover.\nAdvertise in The ijouanza.\nRawhide\nPrivate auto leaves Tonopah Sun\nday morning; two seats not engaged.\nInquire Bonanza office. 1-17 3t\nThere are genuine, worth while\nlooking after bargains at McKim's\nstore these days. Why? Because\nthe stock is far too large just now\nand room must be made for spring\ngoods soon to arrive.\nPInesalve Carbolized acts like a\npoultice, draws out inflammation and\npoison. Antiseptic healing. For\nchapped hands, Hps, cuts, burns. Sold\nby Tonopah Drug Co.\nThe best of service can be found\nat the Nevada Club; the most magni\nficant establishment west of New\nYork. tf\nJOHN GREGOVICH\nDealer in Fancy and Staple\nGroceries\nFRUITS AND VEGETABLES,\nFISH, POULTRY, ETC.,\nIN SEASON.\nI\nTONOPAH\nNEVADA\nTHE TONOPAH BANKING CORPORATION\nCapital and Surplus Fully Paid $375,000.00\n-iifk.?rLB\".\"k!\"..?\",,\".5\".. \"tA. KxckaiiKe Bought and Sold\nII the Principal Cities of the Halted Slate and Europe.\nORPICER8 AND DIRECTORS\n2t'JSESA.J?tmUmt' JOHJ 8' COOK, Vlee-Prealdeat.\niiUE \"J?'1'' Caahler. R. C. MOORE, Aa.fa.taat Caahler.\nSAFE DEPOSIT BOXES FOR RENT\nPioneer Stables\nSIX-1IOKSK STAGE DAILY\nLeave Tonopah 7:00 a. m. daily Leave Manhattan 7:00 a. m. Jalli\nSUMMERFIELD s JOHNSON, Props.\niUUAUUiiitHUllUllUUllUUlillillwuilllllli.itftytammumiuUlllim1UiuMtMil\nH. J. HALL\nTonopah's New Wholesale\nLIQUOR HOUSE\nIs Now Ready for Business\nThis is the Largest Liquor Establishment in\nSouthwestern Nevada\nLOWER MAIN STREET, NEAR DEPOT\nAll Orders Promptly Attended to\nTvnrnnTTnnffwwTtwwffTTnTrnTTTrmmmmTmTmrrntrriTnnTfTffmTmmwmTmTl\nMINER FOUND IN\nDYING\nCONDITION\nTO LOS ANGELES\nAND\nSALT LAKE CITY\nDaily Trains leave Uuldih-ld at 9.13 a. m. via Imh Vega and Tonopah\nTHItOtftiH SLKEPKK TO US ANGKLKS, where it arrive\nlit H o'clock a. ni. Connection at T.a Vegas with I,os Angeles I.I nil tod for\nSuit Ijiku City and (liicago.\nIitforiiiulion and tirlifts may be ioiiii-, fro in all Iatt Vena and\nTonopah agents or from CJoo. II. Knight, (ion'l Agent, (ioldlleld\nSALT LAKE ROUTE THE DIRECT LINE\nBenjamin .Martin, familiarly known\nabout the city as \"Ben\" Martin,'\ndied suddenly at the Carson Ex\nchange hotel last evening after a:i\nillness of four days. Four days ago\nMartin was found on the Indian\nschool road in an unconscious condi\ntion by Supt. Asbury of the school,\nand brought to the capital. He re\ngained consciousness and was appar\nently becoming better when last night\nabout 9:30 o'clock he suddenly grew\nworse and died within a few min\nutes. The deceased was about 60 years\nold and had been in this section for\nyears, coming here from St. Stanilas,\nProvince of Quebec, Canada. Before\nhis death he told those at his bedside\nthat he had four daughters and two\nsons at the Canadian town. He dH\nnot mention his wife and It is thought\nthat she is dead.\nMartin owned rich mining property\nIn the Pinenut district and has work\ned It alone for eight or ten years.\nThe property adjoins the Zirm\nSchulz property where thousands of\ndollars was taken out by the lucky\nowners. Martin is known to have\nleft some money deposited with the\nState Bank and Trust Company of\nthis city and also about $1600 de\nposited with a San Francisco bank.\nHis friends also believe that he has\nmoney and probably gold burled on\nhis mining property in the Pinenut\ndistrict.\nHe was taken ill while at work\n(here alone and started to the city\nand was overcome while en route and\nfell from his wagon, later being dis\ncovered by Mr. Asbury and brought\nhere. Members of the family at St.\nStanlslHs will be communicated wltii\nat once. Carson N'ews.\n:WWW.'\nill A i\n''IP\nMr\nQ.\nh,4 V\nmil r\nV 1\ni7H\nmi\n'Eg?\n!T, !lV\n1 1 i 1 I. t